{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d70b3df4-399f-4c88-b35f-cb064fd503cd","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. The simplest migration:\n\n```csharp\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n        window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n        window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n        window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n\n        return window;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nAlternatively, subclass `Window` and override `OnCreated()`, `OnStopped()`, and `OnResumed()` directly.\n\n**Key mappings:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window event |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Created` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` |\n\nThere are also `Activated`, `Deactivated`, and `Destroying` events for finer-grained control.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"73d02008-2ab4-4f31-9a23-97c75a1acb27","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent approach is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or override lifecycle methods on the `Window` class. The `Application` class no longer has `OnStart`/`OnSleep`/`OnResume`. Instead, you work with `Window` events like `Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, `Destroying`, or override `CreateWindow` and hook into window lifecycle methods.\n\n\nThe direct mappings are `OnStart` to `Window.Created`, `OnSleep` to `Window.Stopped` or `Deactivated`, and `OnResume` to `Window.Resumed` or `Activated`. You can also create a custom `Window` subclass to override these methods directly, or use `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs` for more granular platform-specific lifecycle handling.\n\nFor the quickest migration, I'd override `CreateWindow` in the `App` class and hook into the window lifecycle events there.","outputTokens":652,"requestId":"0813:187D22:A38292:BDAC23:69F2A8F7"},"id":"243514fe-5871-4d52-9d21-dbb71d73d381","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:57:40.094Z","parentId":"e923e391-d694-4c6a-bdab-9c85b447ee3f"}
